34:38.643 --> 34:40.270
- What do you say?
- Like a date?

34:40.344 --> 34:42.107
No, I didn't mean it like that.

34:42.179 --> 34:43.579
<i>Like an "I feel sorry for you</i>

34:43.648 --> 34:46.139
<i>"because it's your birthday
and you have no plans" dinner.</i>

34:46.217 --> 34:48.879
- You know, one of those.
- Well, I'll tell you what.

34:48.953 --> 34:50.944
You can take me to this party
I have to go to,

34:51.022 --> 34:53.956
because there's no way
I can face going alone.

35:01.332 --> 35:03.766
Yeah, I'm gonna go head over...

35:05.503 --> 35:06.663
Whoa.

35:08.539 --> 35:10.837
I think I'm a little out of my league here.

35:10.908 --> 35:12.739
Yes, you are.

35:17.315 --> 35:20.512
So Emily is what, like,
your college sweetheart?

35:20.585 --> 35:22.553
- It's amazing how you do that.
- What?

35:22.620 --> 35:24.212
The way you take the simplest statement,

35:24.288 --> 35:27.519
and then you twist it with
a completely negative connotation.

35:27.592 --> 35:30.584
- It's really, actually, impressive. I'm amazed.
- I didn't mean to do that.

35:30.661 --> 35:33.095
- But I understand. I get it.
- I actually think it's very sweet.

35:33.164 --> 35:34.563
- See, you did it again.
- Really?

35:34.632 --> 35:36.065
- Yeah.
- I don't even know I'm doing it.

35:36.134 --> 35:39.297
It's probably hard for you to imagine
a relationship based on mutual respect

35:39.370 --> 35:43.204
without even the slightest hint of
whatever you call it, masochism.

35:43.274 --> 35:46.368
Well, if your deal with Emily
is so gosh darn wonderful,

35:46.444 --> 35:48.241
then why don't you just marry her?

35:48.312 --> 35:50.143
What's stopping you?

35:51.282 --> 35:52.544
Nothing.

35:54.218 --> 35:55.549
- Wow.
- Wow.

35:58.623 --> 36:00.488
She gets it tomorrow. I made a reservation

36:00.558 --> 36:02.822
at some fancy French restaurant
on the Upper East Side.

36:02.894 --> 36:06.125
Oh, my God. You're doing it
in front of a room full of strangers?

36:06.197 --> 36:10.861
- Yeah, I am. What's wrong with that?
- No, nothing. I think it shows confidence.

36:10.935 --> 36:11.993
What are you gonna say?

36:12.069 --> 36:14.970
- I'm still working on it. I don't know.
- Oh, you should work on it with me.

36:15.039 --> 36:19.567
You should practice with me.
I'm really good at that. I will be Emily.

36:19.644 --> 36:24.047
I'm Emily, your college sweetheart.
Is there something you wanted to ask me?

36:24.115 --> 36:26.379
- Emily...
- Wait! You've got to get down on your knee.

36:26.450 --> 36:28.418
No, I'm not getting down on my knee.

36:28.486 --> 36:31.011
She'll like it.
She'll like seeing you down on your knee.

36:31.088 --> 36:36.151
- I'm not getting down on my knee.
- Such a mistake. Okay.

36:36.694 --> 36:38.559
- Emily.
- Yes, William.

36:38.629 --> 36:40.995
Don't make me laugh. Emily,

36:41.465 --> 36:42.989
will you,

36:43.834 --> 36:44.858
um,

36:46.704 --> 36:48.171
marry me?

36:48.973 --> 36:52.067
- No.
- Oh, my God.

36:52.143 --> 36:53.974
<i>Well, what do you mean,
"Will you, um, marry me?"</i>

36:54.045 --> 36:55.637
I haven't seen you in weeks!

36:55.713 --> 36:58.841
You don't look happy or excited
about the prospect of our marriage!

36:58.916 --> 37:02.818
You're asking me to give up my freedom,

37:02.887 --> 37:04.286
<i>my joie de vivre</i>

37:04.355 --> 37:06.949
for an institution that fails
as often as it succeeds?

37:07.024 --> 37:10.858
And why should I marry you, anyway?
I mean, why do you wanna marry me?

37:10.928 --> 37:14.386
Besides some bourgeois desire to fulfill
an ideal that society embeds in us

37:14.465 --> 37:17.366
from an early age to promote
a consumer capitalist agenda?

37:17.435 --> 37:18.459
Oh!

37:18.936 --> 37:20.904
Oh, my God!

37:20.972 --> 37:24.135
- You should've got on your knee!
- Just shut up!

37:26.177 --> 37:27.474
Here.

37:28.779 --> 37:31.304
I wanna marry you
because you're the first person

37:31.382 --> 37:33.475
that I want to look at
when I wake up in the morning

37:33.551 --> 37:36.179
and the only one I wanna kiss goodnight.

37:36.254 --> 37:40.054
Because the first time
that I saw these hands,

37:40.791 --> 37:43.351
I couldn't imagine
not being able to hold them.

37:43.427 --> 37:47.090
But mainly, when you love someone
as much as I love you

37:49.700 --> 37:52.032
getting married is the only thing left to do.

37:52.103 --> 37:54.537
So will you...

37:57.541 --> 37:58.667
Um...

38:01.512 --> 38:03.036
marry me?

38:03.914 --> 38:06.144
Definitely. Maybe.

38:07.618 --> 38:09.745
I have to think about it.

38:11.856 --> 38:13.380
Walk me home?

38:23.734 --> 38:26.828
- Do you want a cup of tea?
- Yeah. I'd love one.

38:30.074 --> 38:31.302
Hey.

38:31.375 --> 38:33.707
<i>How come you have so many copies
of Jane Eyre?</i>

38:33.778 --> 38:36.542
- It's a long story.
- Really?

38:37.481 --> 38:39.472
It seems to be about 300 pages or so.

38:41.419 --> 38:43.011
Seriously, why?

38:44.322 --> 38:48.190
For my 13th birthday,
I wanted a pair of gold stud earrings,

38:48.259 --> 38:52.457
<i>and instead my dad bought me
a hardcover copy of Jane Eyre.</i>

38:52.530 --> 38:56.796
And inside, he wrote a beautiful inscription,
which I could care less about at the time

38:56.867 --> 38:59.597
seeing as I was so pissed
about the earrings,

38:59.670 --> 39:04.573
which was tragic as it turned out 'cause
it was the last present he ever gave me.

39:04.642 --> 39:06.041
What do you mean?

39:06.110 --> 39:09.102
He died three weeks later in a car accident.

39:09.547 --> 39:12.710
Jesus. That's awful.

39:13.684 --> 39:15.083
I'm sorry.

39:15.419 --> 39:18.252
- Have you ever read it?
- No.

39:18.322 --> 39:21.416
I read it every year or two.
Each time it's different.

39:21.492 --> 39:23.790
It tells me different things.

39:24.829 --> 39:29.698
Anyhow, when I went away to college,
my mom sold our house

39:29.767 --> 39:32.600
<i>and somewhere along the way,
Jane Eyre got lost.</i>

39:32.670 --> 39:35.935
Now, every time I pass
a second-hand bookstore,

39:36.006 --> 39:38.998
I look for the copy that my dad
bought me for my birthday.

39:40.378 --> 39:41.606
I know I'll never find it.

39:41.679 --> 39:46.514
It's stupid, but it's become this,
like, weird superstitious little...

39:46.584 --> 39:49.917
- It's not stupid.
- Thanks. Hobby.

39:50.788 --> 39:52.722
What are all these?

39:52.857 --> 39:57.021
Oh, these are the ones
I found that have inscriptions.

39:59.730 --> 40:04.030
<i>"With love and hopes and dreams
of second chances. Alice."</i>

40:07.104 --> 40:08.332
What is this?

40:08.406 --> 40:12.206
This is Kurt Cobain.
This is Nirvana. Do you like it?

40:13.144 --> 40:14.736
Yeah, I do.

40:16.280 --> 40:19.113
You think it's ridiculous
that I want to be a politician, don't you?

40:19.183 --> 40:20.946
- Yes.
- Thank you.

40:21.552 --> 40:25.818
No, no, I get the whole politician thing.
It's easy to like you.

40:25.890 --> 40:28.654
That's true. That's very true.

40:28.726 --> 40:32.685
I just wonder if you want people
to like you a little too much.

40:33.097 --> 40:35.031
That's also true.

40:35.099 --> 40:36.999
I should want them to hate me.

40:37.568 --> 40:40.093
I'm gonna start working on that right away.
You got any tips for me?

40:40.171 --> 40:41.832
No, but you're off to a great start.

40:41.906 --> 40:42.964
- Yeah?
- I'm hating you already.

40:43.040 --> 40:44.132
Good.

40:44.208 --> 40:45.766
What do you wanna be when you grow up?

40:45.843 --> 40:48.107
I mean, you're too smart
to be making Xeroxes

40:48.179 --> 40:49.510
- and babysitting.
- No.

40:49.580 --> 40:52.606
- I don't know!
- Whatever else you do.

40:52.683 --> 40:56.312
I don't know,
and I don't know how to know. You know?

40:58.756 --> 41:01.054
You know what I really wanna do

41:01.125 --> 41:04.925
is I wanna go to all those places
that I know nothing about.

41:06.063 --> 41:08.156
I've been saving money.

41:08.232 --> 41:10.291
But I can't even get it together to do that.

41:10.367 --> 41:12.835
Probably because I'm stuck in a rut
with this guy.

41:12.903 --> 41:14.564
You should dump him.

41:14.638 --> 41:19.507
I know that's none of my business,
but you're too good for him.

41:19.877 --> 41:21.242
You are.

41:23.314 --> 41:25.976
- You know what's really cool?
- I don't.

41:26.050 --> 41:29.781
We can just sit here
and we don't have to worry about

41:29.854 --> 41:34.086
- flirting or all the attraction stuff.
- All that stuff.

41:35.192 --> 41:36.523
Very cool.

41:37.061 --> 41:38.187
Yeah.

41:55.045 --> 41:56.876
I got to go.

42:00.951 --> 42:02.316
Dumbass!

43:07.117 --> 43:09.210
- Oh, God.
- There he is!

43:09.286 --> 43:13.052
- Told you he wouldn't be long.
- Hi! I wanted to surprise you!

43:13.123 --> 43:16.490
- I took the red-eye!
- That's incredible!

43:17.394 --> 43:22.559
I was just telling Emily how Arthur sent you
to Albany as part of the advance team.

43:22.633 --> 43:24.624
- Advance team.
- Yeah. How'd it go?

43:24.702 --> 43:27.933
- How'd it go? Man, it went great!
- Great.

43:28.005 --> 43:29.495
- Great.
- Great.

43:30.040 --> 43:33.669
- Are you okay?
- Oh, yeah, I was just getting a little exercise.

43:33.744 --> 43:35.473
- I ran up the stairs.
- Okay.

43:35.546 --> 43:39.915
I'm going to the office. It's...
Got a big day. Nice meeting you.

43:39.984 --> 43:41.076
- And you.
- Okay.

43:41.151 --> 43:42.311
Okay.

43:43.287 --> 43:44.686
Good luck.

43:47.891 --> 43:49.358
- Hi.
- Hi.

43:50.594 --> 43:52.721
- Here.
- Yeah.

43:54.865 --> 43:56.127
Hey.

44:04.341 --> 44:07.538
- It's weird. Your tongue tastes different.
- What?

44:08.312 --> 44:09.870
It tastes different, your tongue.

44:09.947 --> 44:13.576
- That is weird.
- It's not bad. It's just different.

44:14.785 --> 44:17.049
Maybe it's the tap water here.

44:17.121 --> 44:20.522
Or the pH balance...
I don't know what I'm talking about.

44:20.591 --> 44:23.492
Told you New York was gonna change you.

44:24.795 --> 44:27.059
- Could we maybe go for a walk?
- Yeah.

44:27.131 --> 44:29.497
- Just to get some air?
- Yeah, you could see New York.

44:29.566 --> 44:30.760
I would love that.

44:31.168 --> 44:32.760
So, did I ever tell you...
- I was gonna...

44:32.836 --> 44:34.963
- Oh, sorry. No, go.
- What?

44:35.639 --> 44:41.441
I was gonna say, did I ever tell you
about the day my dad proposed to my mom?

44:41.979 --> 44:43.003
No.

44:44.014 --> 44:47.279
Well, Dad was on his way
to meet my mom to propose,

44:47.351 --> 44:51.651
and he runs into his ex-girlfriend,
Caroline Hopper.

44:52.723 --> 44:55.191
And they're talking,
they're looking at each other,

44:55.259 --> 44:57.193
and all these old feelings,
they start coming up.

44:57.261 --> 44:59.388
And he's thinking,

45:00.631 --> 45:03.759
<i>"I could run away right now
with Caroline Hopper,</i>

45:03.834 --> 45:05.529
<i>"be a happy man.</i>

45:05.602 --> 45:07.695
<i>"All I have to do is kiss her."</i>

45:07.771 --> 45:10.831
But instead, he looks up,

45:13.777 --> 45:17.213
and he sees my mom
walking around the corner.

45:17.948 --> 45:21.349
And that moment he knows
that he had no reason to be afraid.

45:21.418 --> 45:23.079
You understand?

45:25.489 --> 45:28.720
Am I Caroline Hopper in this story
or your mom?

45:30.094 --> 45:31.288
Oh, my God! I'm your mom!

45:31.361 --> 45:33.158
- Emily, when I saw you this morning...
- Will, please.

45:33.230 --> 45:34.595
...I knew...
- Put that back in your pocket.

45:34.665 --> 45:36.189
- Just stand up, Will. Stop.
...with absolute clarity.

45:36.266 --> 45:37.563
- Wait, wait, wait.
- I have no reason to be afraid.

45:37.634 --> 45:38.931
- Let's think about this.
- I'm not afraid of this.

45:39.002 --> 45:40.264
It's just like the day that my...

45:40.337 --> 45:41.497
Will!

45:42.139 --> 45:43.470
I slept with Charlie!

45:50.447 --> 45:52.608
I thought we had a plan.

45:53.350 --> 45:57.013
Well, you had a plan, Will.
You have a really big plan!

45:57.087 --> 45:59.078
- Pretty sure we both had that plan.
- I just can't keep pretending

45:59.156 --> 46:00.817
- that I want to be part of it anymore.
- You were there

46:00.891 --> 46:02.518
- when we made it.
- And I didn't know how to tell you.

46:02.593 --> 46:03.855
How do you tell someone
that you care about

46:03.927 --> 46:05.019
that you don't want the same things

46:05.095 --> 46:06.494
- they want anymore?
- The best way?

46:06.563 --> 46:09.361
Definitely having sex with the roommate.

46:11.335 --> 46:13.803
It was cowardly, and I'm sorry.

46:13.871 --> 46:15.600
Oh, good.

46:22.780 --> 46:24.441
You're killing me.

46:26.083 --> 46:28.984
No, I'm not. I'm letting you go.

46:29.920 --> 46:31.979
'Cause if we stay together, Will,
we're gonna be miserable.

46:32.055 --> 46:33.283
I'm gonna hold you back from all these...

46:33.357 --> 46:36.622
- That's not true.
...incredible dreams that you have.

46:36.693 --> 46:39.526
And then, eventually,
you're totally gonna hate me for it.

46:39.596 --> 46:40.858
- No.
- Yes.

46:40.931 --> 46:44.128
Will, I don't want that,
and you don't want that.

46:45.035 --> 46:46.434
Trust me.

46:51.074 --> 46:53.975
You're gonna be just fine, Mr. Hayes,

46:54.912 --> 46:56.573
without me.

46:57.981 --> 46:59.073
Wow.

46:59.583 --> 47:00.777
Yeah.

47:01.752 --> 47:02.878
Wow.

47:03.587 --> 47:06.818
<i>Here is Tom Brokaw in New York.</i>

47:06.890 --> 47:09.484
<i>Good evening. Bill Clinton may have
been wounded in New York,</i>

47:09.560 --> 47:11.391
<i>but the big question tonight is,
to what degree?</i>

47:11.461 --> 47:14.862
<i>Because, after all, he is the big survivor,
indeed, the victor</i>

47:14.932 --> 47:18.390
<i>in the New York primary
and by a comfortable margin.</i>

47:33.617 --> 47:36.142
<i>Goes 'round the moon</i>

47:36.620 --> 47:41.387
<i>I see the passion in your eyes</i>

47:41.458 --> 47:46.361
<i>Sometimes it's all a big surprise</i>

47:46.430 --> 47:50.696
<i>'Cause there was a time when all I did</i>

48:04.581 --> 48:06.310
Hey.

48:06.617 --> 48:08.312
Congratulations.

48:08.886 --> 48:11.354
I hear they asked you to stay on.
You must be very happy.

48:11.421 --> 48:15.323
Yeah, yeah, he did, and I am.
Very, very happy.

48:15.392 --> 48:17.952
Really? Why do I feel
like I should hide the razor blades?

48:18.028 --> 48:19.689
And the staplers and those scissors?

48:19.763 --> 48:23.460
I'll be fine. But this song,
it's an excellent cure for the will to live.

48:23.533 --> 48:26.593
I know. What about the dancing?
Make that end.

48:29.873 --> 48:32.637
I'm sorry about the other night.

48:32.709 --> 48:35.542
It's okay. I just didn't think
that Lucas would approve.

48:35.612 --> 48:38.479
- Or Emily, for that matter.
- Well.

48:38.548 --> 48:42.382
Besides, you and me,
it'd kind of be like cats and dogs.

48:43.086 --> 48:44.747
Yeah. Yeah.

48:46.156 --> 48:49.683
- Oil and water.
- Sandpaper and bare ass.

48:49.760 --> 48:51.887
- That's gross. That's just gross.
- You'd be the ass.

48:51.962 --> 48:53.054
Yeah. No, thank you.

48:53.130 --> 48:54.461
- I'd be honored.
- Lennon and McCartney.

48:54.531 --> 48:56.158
- They were good together.
- Yeah, while it lasted,

48:56.233 --> 48:58.929
and then they couldn't even be friends.

49:00.504 --> 49:04.270
- I think we can, at least, manage that.
- I think we could.

49:07.411 --> 49:09.402
<i>- Enchant.
- Yeah. Salud.</i>

49:13.450 --> 49:15.384
- Come on, let's dance.
- No.

49:15.452 --> 49:16.942
- Why?
- Okay.

49:23.527 --> 49:25.927
You ready?
- Yeah.

49:36.206 --> 49:38.071
Guess that's it for Emily.

49:38.141 --> 49:42.134
I can't believe that
she rehearsed with Charlie.

49:43.647 --> 49:48.107
- I can't believe it, either.
- That leaves April. Maybe Summer.

49:48.185 --> 49:50.415
- Anybody else?
- I was too busy.

49:50.487 --> 49:52.853
I was too busy working on the campaign.

49:52.923 --> 49:54.584
Anyway, when Clinton got elected,

49:54.658 --> 49:55.886
<i>Russell and I started our own
consulting firm,</i>

49:57.060 --> 49:59.722
<i>and we worked on campaigns for everybody.</i>

49:59.796 --> 50:01.286
<i>City council, state senate.</i>

50:01.365 --> 50:03.356
We even did one for the local dog catcher.

50:03.433 --> 50:07.335
That's very interesting, Dad,
but what about girlfriends?

50:07.404 --> 50:10.396
- What about Mom?
- Well, I started dating again.

50:10.474 --> 50:14.205
- But nothing serious.
- What about April? What happened to her?

50:14.277 --> 50:17.906
Well, a week after Kurt Cobain died,
she broke up with her boyfriend.

50:17.981 --> 50:19.448
<i>She went traveling.</i>

50:19.516 --> 50:22.417
<i>She traveled all over the world,
just like she always dreamed of doing.</i>

50:22.486 --> 50:26.149
<i>And she says
that it was because of something</i>

50:26.223 --> 50:28.088
<i>that I said to her on her birthday.</i>

50:28.158 --> 50:31.150
<i>Anyway, we started writing postcards.
We started writing letters.</i>

50:31.228 --> 50:34.561
<i>And before I knew it, even though
we were separated by entire worlds,</i>

50:34.631 --> 50:36.656
<i>we became great friends.</i>

50:41.238 --> 50:44.571
<i>It was 1994,
and New York was full of new life.</i>

50:44.641 --> 50:46.370
<i>More jobs, more money.</i>

50:46.443 --> 50:49.935
<i>That was the start of the Internet.
And overnight, everyone in Manhattan</i>

50:50.013 --> 50:51.002
<i>had a cell phone.</i>

50:51.081 --> 50:52.105
Can you hear me now?

50:52.182 --> 50:54.013
<i>Which they never put down.</i>

50:55.886 --> 51:01.552
<i>And then, our old boss, Arthur Robredo
gave Russell and me our first big break.</i>

51:01.625 --> 51:03.217
- This just came for you.
- Thanks.

51:03.293 --> 51:07.423
<i>I had finally made it inside the room.</i>

51:07.898 --> 51:09.195
- Gareth.
- Hayes.

51:09.266 --> 51:10.528
Good morning.

51:10.600 --> 51:12.261
Hey, let's get this party started.

51:12.969 --> 51:14.334
What's the word from upstate?

51:14.404 --> 51:17.168
<i>For the first time,
New York was coming to me,</i>

51:17.240 --> 51:19.401
<i>instead of the other way around.</i>

51:19.476 --> 51:22.809
<i>"The most endangered species in our nation</i>

51:22.879 --> 51:25.712
<i>"isn't a big woodpecker
